stylometry: When managing products in inventory, there needs to be a balence between the capacity of inventory and the demand for the product. A company needs to have enough inventory to satisfy the demand, but also not have huge amounts of inventory that would cost money to warehouse or could even expire depending on the products. Fixed costs of ordering and producing are involved, and the choice to order large amounts less frequently could lower order costs but raise holding costs (cost to house the products) or order less amounts frequently will lessen holding costs but raise order costs and could also possibly lead to shortage/penalty costs for not havin enough inventory on hand to satis fy demand. The EOQ model determines the best choice for a given situation and looks to minimize all costs. money can be tied up in inventory for a business that could be spread out differently.
